00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:14,000
Which of us can do that here? It's almost impossible.

201
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:34,000
Anyway, we worked together for two or three days, and then I, very interested in music, and the also Philharmonic, played downtown, and I got on the tram one time, went down to the town.

202
00:23:34,000 --> 00:23:45,000
Oh, I think, oh, in the first few days I was there, I decided I needed to have my own car.

203
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:52,000
There were very few cars, and also at that time, my use to it today is one of the busiest places in town.

204
00:23:52,000 --> 00:24:00,000
I mean, it's bumper to bumper getting through there. When I lived there, it was rarely a car, and they were all pre-war things.

205
00:24:00,000 --> 00:24:10,000
The country was so destitute, of so devoid of money that cars were very, very hard to come by.

206
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:20,000
But anyway, I could buy a car, there were agencies there, but I had to pay for it in the foreign currency, and I had to agree to sell it.

207
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:28,000
I mean, I had to agree to export the car.

208
00:24:28,000 --> 00:24:38,000
It had a special license plate on it, indicated it had a Q number on it, which means owned by a foreigner, and means you didn't buy tax.

209
00:24:38,000 --> 00:24:46,000
So the upside of all this was that if I sold the car in the country at the end, tax would have to be paid on it at that stage.

210
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:55,000
So I bought this car. So I drove the downtown to go to the symphony here a few weeks later.

211
00:24:55,000 --> 00:25:02,000
And as I walked in, they're still picking up her ticket as I was picking up mine.

212
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:11,000
So we sat together, enjoyed the symphony, and afterward I asked her if she'd like to have a after concert snack.

213
00:25:11,000 --> 00:25:20,000
And so we went to a restaurant of famous place called Blooms that is still there, and we had a big cheese spread and had a good time together.

214
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:24,000
And we again date regularly.

215
00:25:24,000 --> 00:25:34,000
And the upside of all that was that after my year there, I went back to the States.

216
00:25:34,000 --> 00:25:41,000
And there was a decent eye we're thinking of getting married.

217
00:25:41,000 --> 00:25:46,000
And I wasn't quite ready to commit because I hadn't quite recovered from my first marriage.

218
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:59,000
But at any rate, I got back to the States, and then I proposed to her, and I came back the following summer, which is 54, and we were married in Oslo.

219
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:06,000
And that, say, 54, I guess we've now been married 57 years.

220
00:26:06,000 --> 00:26:10,000
Anyhow, that was a romantic outcome.

221
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:13,000
And I got, I've often speculated about this later.

222
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:22,000
Suppose that full-bright application that I had applied for to Holland to Belgium had been successful.

223
00:26:22,000 --> 00:26:27,000
My life would have been quite different from what it is now.

224
00:26:27,000 --> 00:26:31,000
Such things, fate turns on.

225
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:35,000
Were there any problems with your family?

226
00:26:35,000 --> 00:26:39,000
How do you mean marrying a fair foreigner?

227
00:26:39,000 --> 00:26:44,000
Her mother had died a couple of years before I arrived.

228
00:26:44,000 --> 00:26:48,000
She had a sister and a father.

229
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:53,000
A father worked in a bank, a personal manager of a bank.

230
00:26:53,000 --> 00:27:05,000
And she had an aunt, the sister of her mother, that lived upstairs in the apartment building.

231
00:27:05,000 --> 00:27:12,000
My wife's family is going back to generations as a distinguished one.

232
00:27:12,000 --> 00:27:27,000
They came from Denmark, and my wife's great-great-grandfather was the foreign minister of Denmark.

233
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:35,000
And he and his, one of his siblings, founded essentially the New York Times of Denmark,

234
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:38,000
called Poulotique.

235
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:42,000
And so the family had an interest in that newspaper.

236
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:52,000
One of the other brothers was a distinguished newspaper, my name is Critique.

237
00:27:52,000 --> 00:27:56,000
The name is well-known.

238
00:27:56,000 --> 00:27:59,000
It's called Brandes.

239
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:03,000
You can find books written about the Brandes family in Denmark.

240
00:28:03,000 --> 00:28:10,000
It's a great-great-grandfather and great-great-great uncle.

241
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:16,000
So anyway, Elisa's mother stemmed from this group,

242
00:28:16,000 --> 00:28:20,000
as did her aunt upstairs, who became kind of a surrogate mother to her,

243
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:24,000
after her own mother died.

244
00:28:24,000 --> 00:28:31,000
So we came back, Elisa's father.

245
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:34,000
I enjoyed him a lot.

246
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:36,000
He was very taciturn.

247
00:28:36,000 --> 00:28:42,000
Some Norwegians don't say very much, but I think he was pleased that I could speak to him in his language.

248
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:44,000
He didn't know.

249
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:50,000
He could speak a few words in some words of English, but he wasn't as comfortable in it.

250
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:56,000
So we hit it off very well.

251
00:28:56,000 --> 00:29:04,000
And Elisa's aunt too, she was a nutrition type person.

252
00:29:04,000 --> 00:29:09,000
She had beautiful furniture and paintings and so on.

253
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:15,000
And her husband was a distinguished Norwegian scholar and so on.

254
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:19,000
Very wealthy.

255
00:29:19,000 --> 00:29:27,000
And this family, Elisa's aunt, uncle, and her cousin, to whom she is still very close.

256
00:29:27,000 --> 00:29:29,000
We see them quite often.

257
00:29:29,000 --> 00:29:32,000
They have a lot of fancy stuff.

258
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:35,000
They have paintings by Toulouse with track.

259
00:29:35,000 --> 00:29:45,000
And they have munk originals, Edward munk, watercolors and lithographs and so on in their house.

260
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:48,000
That was just something on the wall.

261
00:29:48,000 --> 00:29:53,000
I was pretty impressed by all that.

262
00:29:53,000 --> 00:29:57,000
So after we were married, I...

263
00:29:57,000 --> 00:30:00,000
Do you have a Norwegian lady?

264
00:30:00,000 --> 00:30:04,000
No, we married in the city hall in Norway.

265
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:07,000
You haven't been in Norway, have you?

266
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:12,000
No, well, they have an absolutely beautiful city hall.

267
00:30:12,000 --> 00:30:27,000
And it's got marvelous paintings around that huge murals on the wall that depict the development and evolution of the Norwegian nation.

268
00:30:27,000 --> 00:30:35,000
And outside they have some carved, huge carved wooden figures from North mythology.

269
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:41,000
Wooden is there on his eight-legged horse with two ravens ahead, all in wood you can see up there.

270
00:30:41,000 --> 00:30:44,000
So no, we were married.

271
00:30:44,000 --> 00:30:50,000
These had a reinstall license before I arrived and we were married in this office.

272
00:30:50,000 --> 00:30:55,000
It was a civil wedding.

273
00:30:55,000 --> 00:31:10,000
I'm not sure, but I think, as far as I know, a lot of the Norwegian weddings are done in that fashion, at least of the generation that Lisa stems from.

274
00:31:11,000 --> 00:31:19,000
So after we were married, we fussed around a while because we had to get a visa for her.

275
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:27,000
And that's a story which irritates me still.

276
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:31,000
So we applied for a visa down at the embassy.

277
00:31:31,000 --> 00:31:39,000
And the embassy is very worried that there are foreigners that want to marry American citizens simply to get into the country.

278
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:43,000
And you have to jump through a whole bunch of hoops.

279
00:31:43,000 --> 00:31:49,000
And time went on, one wait, turned it two, turned into three, and so on.

280
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:55,000
And no word, no word at all.

281
00:31:55,000 --> 00:32:02,000
And so I finally wrote to a friend of mine that I had met at Caltech and then was working as a scientist working in Washington.

282
00:32:02,000 --> 00:32:05,000
And I explained the situation to him.

283
00:32:05,000 --> 00:32:17,000
And he pulled some strings and discovered that the application was sitting on the desk someplace in a pile of papers and they were working through and they would get to it.

284
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:31,000
So I virtually blew my top at this because here I am sitting in Oslo and not getting paid because I'm not working waiting for some secretary to clear my application for the visa.

285
00:32:32,000 --> 00:32:38,000
So I wrote to my congressman in Pasadena.

286
00:32:38,000 --> 00:32:48,000
And he wrote back on the other dismissal, dismissive letters saying we have to make absolutely certain that these marriages are not marriages of convenience.

287
00:32:48,000 --> 00:32:52,000
And you can imagine how I felt about it.

288
00:32:52,000 --> 00:32:56,000
He was a conservative Republican.

289
00:32:56,000 --> 00:33:05,000
I probably turned him into a Democrat forever, but anyhow, eventually we got the visa.

290
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:12,000
We got on the plane, flew to Washington, spent a night there, then went on the Pasadena.

291
00:33:12,000 --> 00:33:18,000
And my wife was very tired at this time and discouraged.

292
00:33:18,000 --> 00:33:27,000
And when Norway had beautiful atmospheric conditions, you could breathe deeply and the sky was clear.

293
00:33:27,000 --> 00:33:39,000
And we landed in a heavy smog time in LA and she later says she felt like getting right back on the next plane and going home without experience.

294
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:56,000
So we stayed there and I went back to work at Caltech as a senior research fellow now and continued until I learned about the job at Oregon State.

295
00:33:56,000 --> 00:34:00,000
Now, shall I go on to that?

296
00:34:00,000 --> 00:34:03,000
No, I have more questions about Caltech.

297
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:06,000
I'll take a little bit more in this.

298
00:34:06,000 --> 00:34:15,000
So it sounds to me like the first experience you have that trust was with Schumaker?

299
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:18,000
No, it was Dick Badger.

300
00:34:18,000 --> 00:34:23,000
I did a lecture on the fraction with Schumaker, which is a different technique.

301
00:34:23,000 --> 00:34:27,000
Some people call it an electron spectroscopy, but it is not.

302
00:34:27,000 --> 00:34:32,000
I'm sorry?

303
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:36,000
Can it be bundled under the heading of crystallography or is that a separate discipline?

304
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:42,000
It's a separate discipline, but it's similar to the crystallography in the sense that you measure a diffraction pattern.

305
00:34:42,000 --> 00:34:56,000
The diffraction patterns are very, very different because I'm looking at molecules on the gas and x-ray diffraction looks at molecules and is in a crystal or at least in a condensed phase.

306
00:34:56,000 --> 00:35:00,000
So how would you classify your discipline in the view?

307
00:35:00,000 --> 00:35:03,000
Well, how do you mean classify it?

308
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:08,000
It's a technique for studying the sizes and shapes of individual molecules.

309
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:15,000
So would you call yourself a physical chemistry with infrastructure or chemistry?

310
00:35:15,000 --> 00:35:20,000
So I guess I'm wondering at what point did you decide this is something you want to pursue?

311
00:35:20,000 --> 00:35:22,000
Oh, I see.

312
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:35,000
Well, when I was at Caltech, as I say, I started doing organic reaction mechanisms for a year, then I did electron diffraction.

313
00:35:35,000 --> 00:35:45,000
And in the course of this, I did some crystal structure with two other people.

314
00:35:45,000 --> 00:35:52,000
And then I did spectroscopy with Dick Badger, so I had four different experiences there.

315
00:35:52,000 --> 00:36:03,000
Now, this is a little unusual because at this institution, it's rare that a student works for more than one person in the course of getting his or her degree.

316
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:09,000
Usually you pick a supervisor and you work on his projects and write up a thesis and you're out of here.

317
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:19,000
But I worked and in my thesis, the Badger work, of course, I was a post-cultural fellow at that time.

318
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:28,000
But in the course of getting my degree, I did three things and all of these things were written up in my thesis in different sections.

319
00:36:28,000 --> 00:36:44,000
That's a little unusual. Probably a little unusual for Caltech, too, in that people often do two different things, but three with three different people is quite different.

320
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:57,000
I don't know whether I mentioned that crystal structure was very interesting. It had to do with a compound arsenal benzene, which has a formula

321
00:36:57,000 --> 00:37:05,000
that I can describe verbally as two benzene rings and two arsenic atoms.

322
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:17,000
It was generally thought that the benzene rings are hooked to the arsenic atoms and two arsenic atoms are joined together by a double bond, as we say in the language.

323
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:28,000
But it was pretty well understood at that time that arsenic doesn't like to form double bonds very readily, and particularly with a compound like this,

324
00:37:28,000 --> 00:37:34,000
there's no opportunity, for example, no oxygen, so round to form double bonds.

325
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:42,000
So it was widely thought to be a dimer the one I described, just two units hooked together.

326
00:37:42,000 --> 00:37:57,000
But we suspected that wasn't true, and so when we looked at it, we found that there actually was a six-member ring of arsenic atoms with these benzene rings flopping off, one off of each arsenic atom.

327
00:37:57,000 --> 00:38:03,000
So it was a hexamer, really, and a very nice molecule.

328
00:38:03,000 --> 00:38:16,000
The interesting thing about this is, many years later, I got a photocopy and a large photocopy, which I still have.

329
00:38:16,000 --> 00:38:22,000
This is before Euro became the official currency of Europe.

330
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:27,000
I have a 200-mark German banknote.

331
00:38:27,000 --> 00:38:30,000
Now 200 marks was a big bucks in those days.

332
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:43,000
And on it is a picture, a man who is responsible for discovering the first arsenicles in use for treating syphilis in particular.

333
00:38:44,000 --> 00:39:08,000
Well, one of the arsenicles used was I gather was our senomenzine, because on this banknote our paper is actually cited with the three authors and the date, which happens to be wrong, but at any rate it's on the face of this banknote.

334
00:39:08,000 --> 00:39:12,000
I thought that was lots of fun.

335
00:39:12,000 --> 00:39:19,000
So, anyway, that's what I did at Caltech.

336
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:22,000
And I call myself a structure chemist.

337
00:39:22,000 --> 00:39:36,000
So the thing that led me into electron diffraction was, you have to realize, this was 50 odd years ago now, it was kind of a cutting-edge technology.

338
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:53,000
It was the best way, everything considered, of determining the sizes and shapes and motions of individual molecules that are unaffected by the presence of others.

339
00:39:53,000 --> 00:39:58,000
This was a crystal structure, of course, of molecules that are all packed together.

340
00:39:58,000 --> 00:40:07,000
And the other technique that works also on the same phase is microinspectroscopy.

341
00:40:07,000 --> 00:40:16,000
But in order for microinspectroscopy to succeed, molecule has to have a dipole moment and a lot of them don't.

342
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:26,000
Our senomenzine, for example, would not have, so you can't study a lot of things, but we can study anything we can get into the gas phase, select on the fraction.

343
00:40:26,000 --> 00:40:40,000
So, I decided I would continue with that work, because I like what I was doing with Schumaker at Caltech, and that's what got me started.

344
00:40:40,000 --> 00:40:49,000
So you've been seeing Schumaker and Cori, I'm interested in knowing a little bit more about what they were like, because their personalities were like a few centimeters socially.

345
00:40:49,000 --> 00:41:09,000
Well, I can tell you, well Schumaker, in my way of thinking he was a brilliant scientist, but not aggressive in the sense that he pushed like a lot of people.

346
00:41:09,000 --> 00:41:21,000
You know, in science, it isn't always enough to have talent.

347
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:33,000
You have to be a salesman as well, and people like Linus Pauling, he is a tremendous salesman because he had a personality that took in the whole room.

348
00:41:33,000 --> 00:41:40,000
So his, and yet a sense of humor in his lectures were very, very heavily attended.

349
00:41:40,000 --> 00:41:52,000
People had come from miles around to hear him, and I've heard him lecture to packed halls in several foreign countries.

350
00:41:52,000 --> 00:42:00,000
For other people, who are distinguished also, but have a very tiring personality.

351
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:10,000
And some of these are one noble prizes, you know, but they don't have a public acclaim that a person like Pauling does

352
00:42:10,000 --> 00:42:21,000
or Ahmed Surwel knows from contact. And these guys sell themselves, you know, and there are other people too.

353
00:42:21,000 --> 00:42:31,000
So Schumaker was a brilliant scientist and a very critical thinker.

354
00:42:31,000 --> 00:42:34,000
He was amazing in that respect.

355
00:42:34,000 --> 00:42:42,000
He was so highly regarded that Pauling used to come down and bounce his ideas off of Schumaker.

356
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:46,000
He would come into the office, you know, and talk to Schumaker and say,

357
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:51,000
Werner, what do you think of this? And he would describe something.

358
00:42:51,000 --> 00:43:02,000
And other people, the organic chemists from the Third Floor of Caltech,

359
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:11,000
names are getting harder for me to come by quickly, would come down, talk to him about various problems they had.

360
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:18,000
And he was like a bulldog. He couldn't let go of a problem. He would analyze it, turn it around upside down,

361
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:24,000
and if this, that, et cetera, et cetera. These people would sit and listen very carefully to him.

362
00:43:24,000 --> 00:43:34,000
So that's the kind of guy he was. He also, we went hiking in the Sierra backpacking together.

363
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:39,000
We became close personal friends, as well as my, me being his student.

364
00:43:39,000 --> 00:43:45,000
So we did hikes in the high Sierra's on a couple of occasions.

365
00:43:45,000 --> 00:43:54,000
I used to go every summer for, anyway, one to two weeks backpacking in the high Sierra.

366
00:43:54,000 --> 00:44:02,000
So we would do that. And he was eager and interested in that.

367
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:12,000
There are a host of interesting events, but you see, I'm not quite sure how much of this I should go into,

368
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:20,000
but let me talk about Cori. Cori was a, he was a very nice man.

369
00:44:20,000 --> 00:44:29,000
And he helped me a great deal when Schumacher wasn't there in that last year when I was writing up my thesis.

370
00:44:29,000 --> 00:44:36,000
And he was a crystallographer.

371
00:44:36,000 --> 00:44:44,000
And I don't remember the details, so I won't try to recite them, but I've read them.

372
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:58,000
You can get them. The Caltech archives tell all about polling, encountering Cori and inviting him to come to Caltech.

373
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:04,000
So at any rate, he suffered from some kind of a nervous disorder.

374
00:45:04,000 --> 00:45:14,000
It was not Parkinson's in that he had some ticks that would cause his whole arm to move a little bit.

375
00:45:14,000 --> 00:45:23,000
And when he walked, he walked sometimes with a little bit of motion.

376
00:45:23,000 --> 00:45:29,000
And I'm not quite sure what it was, but that was not evident in the speech when you talked to him.

377
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:37,000
And when he was sitting down, you didn't see any Parkinson's like motion at all for me.

378
00:45:37,000 --> 00:45:42,000
But he would come to see me, and I could see him in a time I wanted.

379
00:45:42,000 --> 00:45:49,000
He was responsible for a very large, excuse me, laboratory.

380
00:45:49,000 --> 00:46:04,000
He was headed up by a guy who was making compounds of the sort that polling was interested in that played a role ultimately in his formulation of the Alpha helix.

381
00:46:04,000 --> 00:46:14,000
So I don't know much more about him than just that.

382
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:22,000
To this day, I'm very grateful for what he did for me in the time of Schimmick's absence.

383
00:46:22,000 --> 00:46:24,000
Do you know Dan Campbell?

384
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:29,000
Yes. Dan was a very nice guy too and he had a very nice wife.

385
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:39,000
I knew Dan Campbell quite well because there was a very free social order at Caltech.

386
00:46:39,000 --> 00:46:44,000
All kinds of parties with the students, postdocs and the faculty.

387
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:51,000
You have a student party, you know, and everybody would be invited and Dick Badger would show up with his wife and Dan and his wife would show up.

388
00:46:51,000 --> 00:46:54,000
And others as well.

389
00:46:54,000 --> 00:46:59,000
Polling didn't come to these parties as far as I know.

390
00:46:59,000 --> 00:47:08,000
I don't remember ever seeing him there, but I do remember a number of them in which people from physics can Dick Feynman showed up in a number of these.

391
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:13,000
I heard Feynman play his bongo drums at these parties.

392
00:47:13,000 --> 00:47:18,000
So Campbell was a nice guy.

393
00:47:18,000 --> 00:47:22,000
He had a medical problem which was solved.

394
00:47:22,000 --> 00:47:28,000
He had colon cancer and they removed a large tumor from his colon.

395
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:33,000
But I don't think he ever suffered a recurrence of that.

396
00:47:33,000 --> 00:47:42,000
He was what was called an immunochemus and that was something that Polling was interested in at the time and immunochemus straight.

397
00:47:42,000 --> 00:47:47,000
So does that answer your question about what I knew about Campbell?

398
00:47:47,000 --> 00:47:50,000
Did you ever buy any chance to eat Roger Hayward?

399
00:47:50,000 --> 00:47:51,000
Yes.

400
00:47:51,000 --> 00:47:52,000
